# Therapy outcomes for neurodiverse couples: Exploring a solution‐focused approach
**Autores**: Not specified
**Año**: 2021
**Journal**: Journal of Marital and Family Therapy 0.0:null-null
**DOI/Link**: N/A

## Abstract
Abstract
The need for clinical approaches that address romantic re-
lationship concerns of adults with autism spectrum disorder 
(ASD) has been essentially overlooked. There are a grow-
ing number of recommendations in the available literature 
to increase the availability and evaluation of treatment 
approaches that are appropriate for couples that include 
an adult with ASD. The aim of the present study was to 
explore clinical outcomes of a neurodiverse couple who 
participated in twelve sessions of solution-­focused brief 
therapy. Our findings indicated both partners experienced 
improvement in the target complaints, communication and 
emotional awareness. On the other hand, each partner had 
a different trajectory of change in relationship satisfaction 
over the course of treatment. Directions for future research 
and implications for couple therapy with adults diagnosed 
with ASD are discussed.
K E Y W O R D S
autism, couples therapy, solution-­focused brief therapy
[Correction added on 14th May 2021, after first online publication: the text 'Aautism' changed to 'autism']
