PARKER et al.
been recommendations in the ASD literature to increase the availability and evaluation of treatment 
approaches that are appropriate for adults with ASD (Nathenson & Zablotsky, 2017). The existing 
research generally focuses on interventions to improve employment skills, transition to higher educa-
tion, and independent living skills (Gray et al., 2014; Grob et al., 2019; Sarrett, 2018). However, the 
need for clinical approaches that address romantic relationship concerns of adults with ASD has been 
essentially overlooked. In fact, couples who include an individual with ASD and a neurotypical (NT) 
partner, (i.e., neurodiverse couples) report significant difficulties finding mental health professionals 
with any experience or basic understanding of neurodiverse couples (Smith et al., 2020). This over-
sight is likely due to the outdated assumption that individuals with ASD have no interest in dating or 
marriage (Kellaher, 2015). More recent findings, however, overwhelmingly suggest that adults with 
ASD report similar levels of relationship interest, knowledge, and experience as their typically devel-
oping peers (Cheak-­Zamora et al., 2019; Dewinter et al., 2017; Hartmann et al., 2019).
Despite sexual and romantic relationship interest, individuals with autism may have deficits related 
to necessary skills and experiences that contribute to positive relationship outcomes. For example, 
communication skills, affect regulation, and cognitive flexibility are common deficits associated with 
ASD that also affect romantic relationship functioning (Dijkhuis et al., 2019; Wilson et al., 2019). 
Although, the severity of autism-­related symptoms does not reduce individuals’ relationship or sexual 
history (Strunz et al., 2017). That is, adults with ASD are involved in or have experience with romantic 
relationships regardless of the severity of relationship skill deficits. Smith et al. (2020) found that all 
participants in the study of neurodiverse couples (N = 13) reported that most relationship counselors 
were not helpful and did not support the needs of both partners. Systemically trained couple therapists 
are particularly qualified to address interpersonal communication and emotional regulation concerns 
in the context of romantic relationships (Halford et al., 2016; Rathgeber et al., 2019). However, many 
marriage and family therapists (MFTs) believe that addressing concerns of those with a developmen-
tal disability, such as ASD is outside their scope of expertise or qualifications (Solomon & Chung, 
2012). As a result of limited MFT training and clinical research with developmental disabilities, it 
is yet unknown if prominent couple therapy approaches are appropriate when working with couples 
in which one or both partners have been diagnosed with ASD. The aim of the present study was to 
explore the application of solution-­focused brief therapy (SFBT) to achieve treatment outcomes of a 
married couple that includes a spouse with ASD. SFBT was applied as the clinical approach due to the 
growing recognition as an appropriate clinical approach to meet the needs of families of children with 
autism (Finlayson et al., 2019; Parker et al., 2020) but has yet to be evaluated for use with romantic 
relationships of adults with ASD.
Autism and development
Autism spectrum disorder is broadly characterized by deficits in social interaction related to commu-
nication, restricted interests, and repetitive behaviors (American Psychiatric Association, 2013). More 
specifically, autism-­associated behaviors may include a lack of flexibility, increased need for soli-
tude, poor receptive and expressive communication of needs, and emotional dysregulation (Dijkhuis 
et al., 2019; Strunz et al., 2017; Wilson et al., 2019). In comparison with their typically developing 
counterparts, children with ASD struggle with social–­emotional reciprocity (e.g., back and forth con-
versation), resulting in fewer friendships and a greater likelihood of peer rejection (Rodda & Estes, 
2018). Adolescents with ASD may develop improved basic social interaction skills (i.e., functional 
communication) among well-­known peers; however, they continue to struggle with more complex 
social behaviors, such as identifying shared interests, asking for help, and initiating conversations 
     |  3
JOURNAL OF MARITAL AND FAMILY THERAPY
(Laghi et al., 2018). As such, autism-­associated behavioral and emotional difficulties in childhood 
often predict less participation in community activity (i.e., paid employment, education) in adulthood 
(Gray et al., 2014). These deficits in social communication limit children's and adolescents’ opportu-
nities for social engagement that would improve the relational skills associated with quality of life in 
adulthood (Helles et al., 2017). Although there is growing attention to the treatment needs for adults 
with ASD, much of the clinical research is specifically focused on developing the social skills neces-
sary for work or academic settings (Grob et al., 2019; Sarrett, 2018). However, there is a notable gap 
in treatment approaches to address romantic relationship concerns, despite the substantial evidence 
indicating adults with ASD participate in sexual and dating relationships.
Autism and romantic relationships
Romantic relationship among adults with ASD are not widely understood, due in large part to 
outdated assumptions that those with autism have limited interest in dating or sexual relationships. 
These perpetuated assumptions are often attributed to the preliminary research on ASD and sexual-
ity conducted in the 1990s, which was primarily based on parent and caregiver report (Kellaher, 
2015). Recently, findings indicate that young adults with ASD exhibit more typical sexual behav-
ior than reported by their parents, suggesting parent-­report of sexual or romantic behavior may be 
misleading (Hartmann et al., 2019). As children with ASD have limited opportunities for social 
development through interactions with peers, lack of sexual or romantic experience among adoles-
cents with ASD may also be due to fewer social opportunities rather than lack of interest (Byers 
et al., 2013). In fact, individuals with ASD who are not involved in a romantic relationship also 
report distress, sadness, and confusion about their relationship status (Cheak-­Zamora et al., 2019; 
Strunz et al., 2017). Unfortunately, parents and autism-­specific professionals (e.g., pediatricians, 
school personnel) are less likely to communicate about sex and relationships with children and 
adolescents with ASD compared with their NT counterparts (Hartmann et al., 2019). These factors 
collectively contribute to the ongoing deficits in romantic and sexual relationships over the life 
span of individuals with ASD.
It is important for clinicians to be aware that contrary to previous assumptions, individuals with 
ASD have relationship interests and experiences that affect their well-­being. Cheak-­Zamora et al. 
(2019) found that although the majority of adolescent and young adult participants were not currently 
in a relationship (80%), the participants still expressed a clear interest in having a relationship. As 
adolescents with ASD gain more independence and privacy from caregivers, those with an interest in 
romantic or sexual relationships will have more opportunities for engagement. Accordingly, current 
research finds the majority of adults with ASD have current or previous experience being in romantic 
relationships (Byers et al., 2013; Dewinter et al., 2017). Perhaps, most importantly, the severity of 
ASD symptoms or skill deficits do not predict one's relationship status or previous relationship expe-
rience (Byers et al., 2013; Strunz et al., 2017). That is, adults with ASD participate in romantic rela-
tionships despite their degree of deficit in relational skills. Existing treatment approaches to improve 
social skills of adults with ASD for the workplace or educational settings do not necessarily generalize 
to other relationships (Grob et al., 2019; Sarrett, 2018). Helles et al. (2017) explain that even when 
social functioning improves over time, romantic relationships demand more subtle understanding of 
social norms that may be challenging for individuals with ASD. As such, there is a clear need for a 
clinical treatment approach to specifically address relationship concerns of couples that include adults 
with ASD.
4  |     
PARKER et al.
Neurotypical romantic partners
In recent years, the effects of NT individuals in neurodiverse relationships are a growing area of 
inquiry. Bostock-­Ling et al. (2012) explored the commonly identified effects on NT women in rela-
tionships with men who have ASD, which included increased social isolation, physical health decline, 
financial concerns, negative self-­mage, and relationship breakdown. In extreme cases, Mendes (2015) 
explains emotional deprivation and unmet emotional needs among NT partners may be described as 
a relational disorder referred to as affective deprivation disorder. Relational concerns among neurodi-
verse couples are frequently due to inconsistent needs and expectations for the relationship (Goldstein 
Hode, 2014; Strunz et al., 2017). Although it may be a reasonable expectation for an NT partner to 
receive emotional support during times of distress, the partner with ASD may not have the social skills 
or experience to meet those expectations. Such discrepancies in emotional needs and expectations 
between partners over the course of the relationship may explain the profound loss of hope for change 
in the relationship described by NT partners (Lewis, 2017). Based on the previously described ASD-­
related difficulties with social and communication skills, psychoeducation and cognitive-­behavioral 
approaches have been suggested to improve these deficits when working with neurodiverse couples 
(Mendes, 2015). Despite the difficulties described by NT partners, neurodiverse relationships develop 
through a similar progression as NT couples, including initial stages of dating and falling in love. 
Individuals in neurodiverse relationships have emphasized the importance of reflecting on the positive 
aspects of their relationship that are embedded in mutual care and support to overcome challenges 
(Smith et al., 2020). There is an identified need for a nondeficit approach to romantic relationships 
between NT partners and individuals with ASD (Goldstein Hode, 2014).
Autism and solution-­focused brief therapy
Solution-­focused brief therapy is a strength-­based, future-­oriented approach that assumes clients pos-
sess an inherent resilience and the necessary resources to reach their treatment goals (Berg & De 
Jong, 1996). A solution-­focused approach aims to punctuate aspects of clients’ lives that are already 
helpful while deemphasizing problem talk (De Jong & Berg, 2013). In a systematic review of SFBT, 
strengths and resources techniques (e.g., scaling, exception-­seeking questions) have demonstrated the 
greatest effectiveness (Franklin et al., 2017). There is a growing body of resiliency-­based research that 
highlights the need for relational interventions that build on strengths to enhance coping and wellbe-
ing among families affected by ASD (Sim et al., 2019), suggesting SFBT is potentially an appropriate 
treatment approach to address the relational effects of ASD. In recent years, SFBT has gained empiri-
cal support for use in a variety of clinical settings that are often involved in ASD treatment, including 
medical settings (Zhang et al., 2018). More specifically, SFBT has also been evaluated as a clinical 
approach that is appropriate to meet the unique, relational needs of families of children with ASD 
(Finlayson et al., 2019; Parker et al., 2020). Despite the application of SFBT to address the needs of 
families affected by ASD, there has yet to be an assessment of SFBT for adults with ASD and their 
partners. This gap in the literature has informed the aim of this study.
The present study
The aim of this study was to evaluate SFBT as a treatment approach for couple therapy with an adult 
diagnosed with moderate ASD and his NT spouse. The couple's response to treatment was assessed by 
     |  5
JOURNAL OF MARITAL AND FAMILY THERAPY
their progress toward client-­derived treatment goals and improvement in overall couple satisfaction 
over 12 sessions of couple therapy using SFBT. Specifically, the present study addressed the follow-
ing research questions:
1A) Do 12 SFBT couple therapy sessions reduce client distress of the presenting concern for a spouse 
diagnosed with ASD?
1B) Do 12 SFBT couple therapy sessions reduce client distress of the presenting concern for the NT 
spouse of a partner diagnosed with ASD?
2A) Do 12 SFBT couple therapy session increase couple satisfaction as reported by a spouse diag-
nosed with ASD?
2B) Do 12 SFBT couple therapy sessions increase couple satisfaction as reported by the NT spouse of 
a partner diagnosed with ASD?

## Key Findings
DISCUSSION
Our purpose in selecting this case study that evaluated SFBT as an appropriate couple therapy ap-
proach for an adult with ASD and his spouse was twofold. First, we were interested in whether SFBT 
interventions would have a comparable effect on client-­derived goals for adults with ASD in couple 
therapy as has been shown for families of children with ASD (Finlayson et al., 2019; Parker et al., 
2020; ). We also sought to evaluate the use of SFBT as a clinical approach to improve general couple 
satisfaction among adults with ASD and their NT partners. Couple therapy generally demonstrates 
a large, positive effect on relationship satisfaction, communication, and emotional intimacy (Roddy 
et al., 2020). As previously discussed, however, individuals with ASD often experience difficulties 
with communication and emotional regulation (Dijkhuis et al., 2019; Wilson et al., 2019), which may 
interfere with relationship satisfaction in one or both partners.
