## Methodology
METHODS
This study was conducted according to the guidelines recommended by the American Psychological 
Association (APA) for evidence-­based case studies (EBCS). Specifically, the APA suggests that 
EBCS should include (1) standardized assessment of a particular symptom(s), (2) a measure of global 
functioning to be completed by the client(s), and (3) a process measure such as the therapeutic alliance 
on a minimum of three separate times during treatment (https://www.apa.org/pubs/journ​als/cfp/evide​
nce-­based​-­case-­study​-­guide​lines). Carlson et al. (2012) explain that EBCS offer greater methodologi-
cal rigor than traditional clinical case studies by integrating verbatim clinical case material (e.g., ses-
sion transcripts) with standardized measures of therapeutic process and outcomes to assess for clinical 
change. In addition to excerpts from session transcripts, this study assessed individual client distress, 
couple satisfaction, and therapeutic alliance using standardized instruments at sessions 1, 4, 8, and 12 
using the following measures.
Measures
Individual distress
To monitor each client's individual distress in relation to the presenting concerns, each client com-
pleted the target complaint (TC) measure (Battle et al., 1966) at the beginning of each therapy session. 
The questionnaire states, “Please record up to three presenting concerns that brought you to therapy. 
Circle the number that best represents your personal degree of discomfort as a result of each issue.” 
Clients are then prompted to rate their degree of discomfort from 1 (i.e., very little) to 10 (i.e., a great 
deal) for each respective issue they have identified. TC was specifically selected to measure therapeu-
tic change in the present study because the goals for change are determined by the clients, which is 
consistent with a solution-­focused approach. TC has demonstrated concurrent validity by correlating 
with other measures of clinical outcomes (Deane et al., 1997). There is some question as to whether 
TC is consistent between therapist and client perceptions of severity of the presenting issue. For the 
current study, however, significant correlation between the therapist and clients’ evaluation of client 
progress was inconsistent with the clinical approach.
6  |     
PARKER et al.
Relationship satisfaction
Clients’ satisfaction with their relationship was used as a secondary indicator of therapeutic change 
and was assessed using the 16-­item Couple Satisfaction Index (CSI-­16; Funk & Rogge, 2007). The 
CSI-­16 is a 16-­item self-­report scale that includes responses on a 6-­point Likert scale resulting in a 
total satisfaction score ranging from 0 (Low) to 81 (High). Example questions include “How reward-
ing is your relationship with your partner?” The CSI-­16 also asks respondents to rate how they feel 
about their relationship on several continuum, such as Interesting–­Boring and Discouraging–­Hopeful. 
The instrument was developed to increase measurement precision of relationship quality and satisfac-
tion in comparison with widely accepted scales, such as the Dyadic Adjustment Scale (DAS; Spanier, 
1976). The CSI-­16 was found to have excellent internal consistency (α = .98) and strong convergent 
and construct validity by high correlations with existing measures of relationship satisfaction (Funk & 
Rogge, 2007). The cutoff score to determine clinical distress levels among couples using the CSI-­16 
is 51.5.
Therapeutic alliance
The relationship between the clients and the therapist was evaluated with the Individual Therapy 
Alliance Scale Revised–­Short Form (ITASr-­SF; Pinsof et al., 2008). The ITASr-­SF is a 15-­item, 
self-­report measure containing responses on a 7-­point Likert scale, ranging from “Completely 
Agree” to “Completely Disagree.” Participants rate their agreement with statements such as 
“The therapist does not understand me” to assess three alliance subscales, therapeutic bonds, 
tasks, and goals. Reliability estimates for the bond and goal subscales of the ITASr-­SF dem-
onstrated sufficient internal consistency with Cronbach's alphas of .66 and .72, respectively. 
However, the tasks subscale has shown poor reliability (α = .25) in the revised version of the 
instrument (Pinsof et al., 2008). Therefore, the tasks subscale was not included in analyses for 
the present study.
Procedure
The participants in this study received couple therapy at a clinic specializing in couple and fam-
ily therapy located in the southeastern United States. Therapists at the clinic who received a new 
client referral from January to December of 2019 were encouraged to invite adult clients with a 
current diagnosis of ASD to participate in a clinical case study during the intake session. Among 
the four clients identified as having an ASD diagnosis who sought therapy at the clinic during this 
time period, this couple was selected for the case study because they initiated couple therapy (vs. 
individual therapy) for a relational concern. With the permission of the couple, the therapist invited 
a member of the research team to speak with the couple during the intake to explain the informed 
consent for research participation that specified all information the couple provided would be de-­
identified prior to analysis. Each member of the couple was given a brief questionnaire every ses-
sion that assessed their level of distress for each presenting concern. Additionally, clients were then 
given two follow up questionnaires (i.e., CSI-­16, TAS) to complete prior to their fourth, eighth, 
and twelfth sessions.
