JOURNAL OF MARITAL AND FAMILY THERAPY
Participants
Couple history
“Shelby” and “Everett” are a married, heterosexual couple with no children. They have been in a 
committed relationship for approximately 5 years. Shelby is a European American woman in her early 
twenties who is employed in the medical field and has enrolled as a part-­time college student. She has 
limited contact with her family of origin and minimal social support. Shelby previously participated 
in therapy during adolescence for childhood trauma. Everett is a European American man in his early 
thirties who is enrolled as a full-­time college student. He has regular contact with his family of origin, 
but difficulty with social relationships. Everett has not participated in therapy previously. However, 
he is in recovery from substance abuse and has been sober for more than 5 years. The couple presented 
for therapy for relational concerns related to a lack of connection and communication difficulties. 
Although these concerns were present throughout the relationship, Everett's recent diagnosis of ASD 
prompted them to seek couple therapy. Specifically, Everett and Shelby both expressed a lack of 
knowledge about ASD after reviewing the testing report together and potential effects the diagnosis 
would have on their relationship.
ASD diagnostic criteria
Everett was self-­referred for an ASD evaluation approximately 2 weeks before the first couple therapy 
session. Although he experienced social anxiety and relationship problems throughout his life, Everett 
was finally prompted to be formally tested for ASD after he was asked to resign from his job for his 
“rudeness.” The assessment was conducted by a clinical psychologist at a local psychology test-
ing and evaluation center.

## Results
Results from the evaluation indicated that Everett's executive functioning 
was within normal limits according to the subscales of the Behavior Rating Inventory of Executive 
Functioning, Adult Version (BRIEF-­A; Gioia et al., 2015). The Global Executive Composite score of 
the BRIEF-­A (T = 56) indicated Everett is below the clinical cutoff score (i.e., T < 65) for attention-­
deficit disorder. There were two notable exceptions, which included the subscale scores on flexibility 
in routine changes (T = 69) and self-­monitoring of social behavior (T = 72). Elevated scores in these 
areas are consistent with difficulties associated with ASD.
Everett's assessment of ASD symptoms was conducted with the Social Responsiveness Scale, 
Second Edition (SRS-­2; Constantino, 2012). SRS subscales showed elevated deficiencies in both of 
the core criteria associated with an ASD diagnosis; Social Communication and Interaction (T = 71) 
and Restricted Interests and Repetitive Behavior (T = 72). The SRS total score (T = 72) is consistent 
with moderate ASD severity. A moderate severity rating is considered clinically significant as it is 
associated with significant interference with social functioning.
Therapist information
The couple and family therapist working with Everett and Shelby was a 28-­year-­old European 
American woman. She was in a marriage and family doctoral program accredited by the Commission 
on Accreditation for Marriage and Family Therapy Education (COAMFTE) and an AAMFT-­approved 
supervisor-­in-­training. The therapist had 5 years of clinical experience and specialized in couple ther-
apy for a variety of presenting concerns. To support fidelity of the clinical approach, the therapist 
8  |     
PARKER et al.
received live, group supervision during each of the therapy sessions (i.e., sessions 1–­12). Supervision 
was conducted by an AAMFT-­approved supervisor with advanced training in SFBT. Consistent with 
the majority of MFTs, the therapist had no prior experience or expertise working with individuals with 
ASD. She therefore consulted with an additional AAMFT-­approved supervisor who had additional 
experience working with clients diagnosed with ASD following sessions one, four, and eight.
Treatment approach
The assigned therapist maintained a present-­focused clinical focus and, consistent with SFBT, she held 
the belief that clients possess the strength, resilience, and wisdom to affect change (De Jong & Berg, 
2013). It was also determined that SFBT was an appropriate clinical approach for the couple due to the 
existing ASD literature identifying the growing need for relational interventions that focus on inherent 
strengths and resiliency among those affected by ASD (Smith et al., 2020). The therapist maintained a 
specific priority to exercise a relational focus that met the needs of both partners without emphasizing 
Everett's recent ASD diagnosis as a focus of treatment. Therapy progressed through the phases of treat-
ment, including assessment, goal development, intervention, and maintenance of progress. It should be 
noted that the assessment phase of treatment occurred over two sessions to obtain the couple's relation-
ship history and Everett's recent ASD diagnostic information. Although such a modification of tradi-
tional SFBT may be considered problem-­saturated, the ASD diagnostic history and areas of functioning 
are inextricably linked to their present lives (Parker et al., 2020). Table 1 includes a brief description of 
the main interventions used by the therapist in each session and the couple's response to the interventions 
used. Further description and transcript excerpts for sessions 1, 4, 8, and 12 are also included.
RESULTS
Target complaints
The clients completed the TC prior to each session of couple therapy (e.g., Session 2–­12) on two pre-
senting concerns that they perceived to be the most critical: Communication and Emotional Awareness. 
The results of the couples’ weekly distress related to Communication and Emotional Awareness are 
shown in Figures 1 and 2. The degree of discomfort related to communication decreased from session 
2 to session 12 for both partners as expected (E = 4 –­ 2; S = 8 –­ 3). There are two intersession change 
trends in the communication TC that are worth noting (see Figure 1). First, the NT partner, Shelby 
indicated substantially higher distress than Everett at session 2. However, Shelby indicated lower dis-
tress than Everett at the end of treatment. Second, there was a greater discrepancy in communication 
distress between Shelby and Everett at the beginning of therapy. At session 12, the couple indicated 
similar levels of distress. By the end of treatment, Shelby experienced a 50% decrease and Everett 
experienced a 20% decrease in distress associated with communication.
The degree of discomfort related to emotional awareness also decreased from session 2 to ses-
sion 12 for both partners as expected (E = 4 –­ 2; S = 7 –­ 1). The intersession changes in Emotional 
Awareness TC for each partner also revealed trends that are clinically relevant (see Figure 2). Similar 
to Communication TC, the discrepancy between partners on Emotional Awareness TC at session 2 
was substantially reduced by session 12. The partners’ scores became notably more synchronous from 
sessions 5 to 10. However, Shelby's reported greater volatility than Everett in her weekly discomfort 
from Emotional Awareness over 12 sessions. For example, sessions 4–­6 and sessions 10–­12 indicated 
