below the cutoff score for clinical distress. She demonstrated a 16% decrease in satisfaction over the 
course of treatment.
Therapeutic alliance
Both Shelby and Everett reported relatively high and consistent bond scores from session 4 to session 
12 (Figure 4). Both partners also reported similar bond scores comparatively. Over the course of ther-
apy, Shelby reported TAS bond scores ranging from 6.7 to 7.0, and Everett reported TAS bond scores 
ranging from 5.7 to 6.0. The couple experienced no change in TAS bond scores from session 4 to ses-
sion 12, as both partners reported the same TAS bond scores from which they started therapy (E = 6.0; 
S = 6.7). The couple demonstrated more significant changes in TAS goal scores over the course of 
therapy. Both partners indicated similar TAS goal scores at session 4 (E = 5.8; S = 5.5). However, the 
couple's TAS task scores diverged from session 4 to session 8, with Everett's score increasing mod-
estly from 5.8 to 6.0 and Shelby's score decreasing from 5.5 to 4.8. By session 12, the couple's scores 
diverged again in opposing directions (E = 4.8; S = 6.3). Everett demonstrated a 14% decrease in TAS 
goal score from session 4 to session 12. However, Shelby reported an 11% increase in TAS goal score 
from session 4 to session 12.
