JOURNAL OF MARITAL AND FAMILY THERAPY
to be more aware of her emotional needs and learn ways to meet her needs that are healthy. We don't 
always communicate what we want and need from each other.” Shelby elaborated, “I agree. Everett 
can get really defensive, even if he doesn't mean to. Then I get mean because he sounds angry to me, 
even when he's not.” In response to Everett's recent ASD diagnosis, the couple expressed their con-
cern and confusion. Shelby explained, “I’ve tried to do a bit of research on my own, as a spouse. And 
there's not much out there for us.” Everett expressed extreme distress after receiving his diagnosis. 
“I’m just worried that I can't fix it. It's scary and I’m terrified, like I’m broken, like I just got a life 
sentence.” The therapist used validation and a strength-­based approach in response to the couple's 
disclosures. “That's a really powerful statement, ‘a life sentence’. Some of the main areas they work 
on with children with ASD are related to making sure they receive a good education and develop the 
ability to have relationships with people who care about them. You seem to have both of those things 
covered. So, the things you've both described are absolutely reasonable goals for therapy that we can 
work toward.”
Session 4
The fourth session was focused on the goal of improving “emotional awareness” between the couple. 
The therapist reviewed the weekly TC submitted by each partner (E = 2; S = 7) by asking “What has 
felt emotionally different between the two of you this week?” Everett explained that Shelby received a 
hurtful email from a family member, and he could see that she was upset while she was reading it. He 
disclosed, “She usually gets upset with me after she argues with her family. But she didn't this time.” 
The therapist used an exception-­seeking question to ask, “How were you able to respond differently 
this time, Shelby?” The couple established that listening to one another and offering statements of 
support were beneficial. Everett highlighted, “Shelby stood up for herself this time instead of avoiding 
the issue with them. And I know that's hard for her.” The therapist used a coping question to identify, 
“How were you able to trust Everett with this issue, when you haven't been able to trust your family?” 
Shelby responded by stating, “He supports me and challenges me to grow as a person instead of ma-
nipulating me with ulterior motives. So, I need to show more patience and change my perspective.” 
The couple were both able to identify examples over the previous week when they experienced or 
demonstrated greater attention to emotional awareness through SFBT exception-­seeking questions.
Session 8
The eighth session was dedicated to the goal of “communication” between the couple. The therapist 
used the TC as a means of scaling the couple's progress over the previous week (E = 4; S = 2). The 
therapist asked a coping question by asking, “It looks like communication went well this week. How 
were you able to have less distress related to your communication?” Everett explained the couple had 
an argument after the previous therapy session in which he expressed to Shelby that her giving him ad-
vice and some of her behavior toward him felt controlling. Everett stated, “We had a great conversa-
tion about it though. I recognized that some of the things she does for me, like when she cooks dinner 
for me, isn't her trying to control me. [To Shelby] It's you wanting to do something nice and showing 
me how much you care about me. And I feel sad about that. Like I asked you not to show me you care.” 
The therapist asked about how the couple was able to work through the argument in a more productive 
way than in the past. Shelby reflected, “He's wired to be more ‘clinical’ in his responses to me. And 
I’ve realized that's okay. I can outsource some things to my friends. He can't be everything to me all of 
14  |     
PARKER et al.
the time.” It should also be noted that Shelby expressed a broader concern about the relationship that 
was not explored further to maintain consistency with an SFBT approach. She stated, “It's just difficult 
because I have to accept so many issues related to your alcoholism and your busy schedule. Now I 
have to accommodate the ASD. There are just a lot of things I’m not allowed to be upset about.” This 
statement may have provided an indication about her corresponding decline in relationship satisfac-
tion for session eight that could inform appropriate modifications to the approach.
Session 12
The final session was aimed at reviewing the progress that the couple had gained throughout the 
course of therapy. Shelby reported that she had an upcoming appointment for individual therapy to 
address childhood abuse. Everett responded, “That's the first time I’ve ever heard you acknowledge 
that you were abused. [To the therapist] That's huge.” Shelby elaborated, “Yeah. We've fought about 
my family a lot. I get defensive about them.” The therapist asked a difference question to review the 
couple's perspective on what has changed as a result of therapy, “What else do the two of you see is 
different for you now?” Shelby identified, “I need to separate myself a little bit. I was too Everett 
crazy. I’m trying to focus more on my interests and myself more.” Everett stated, “I recognize that I 
hyper-­focus on ‘correctness’ as I see it. I follow really close when I disagree with what she's saying. 
In an attempt to improve our communication at a meta-­level, I keep my internal processes to myself. 
My communication is hindered by rigidity and correctness.” The therapist used complimenting to 
emphasize the couple's progress despite significant struggles, “You're doing a lot of emotional and 
psychological work. It's going to be important for you guys to continue to make time for each other. I 
commend you both for all the work you've done and will continue to do.” Everett reiterated, “I know 
we have differences, but I love you and I accept you for who you are. [To the therapist] I give us a 
sense of ‘evenness’. But she's the fun one. Our differences aren't inherently bad.”

## Clinical Significance
CONCLUSION
As the U.S. prevalence of individuals diagnosed with ASD continues to rise, there is likely to be a 
corresponding increase among couples seeking therapy in which one or both partners have ASD. 
Systemically trained couple therapists are ideally suited to address the relational concerns of this 
growing population. SFBT is gaining support as an appropriate clinical approach to meet the rela-
tional needs of those with ASD due to the strength-­based focus and collaborative therapeutic stance. 
Despite the limited generalizability, the results of this study offer an in-­depth evaluation of SFBT as 
a treatment approach for a neurotypically mixed couple. Although both partners reported improve-
ment in the client-­identified TCs, SFBT did not increase overall relationship satisfaction at the end of 
treatment. On-­going research is necessary to further explain these findings and explore appropriate 
solution-­focused modifications or integrations that will improve couple-­related treatment outcomes 
for neurodiverse couples.
